::: abstract
::: abstract-title
Abstract
:::

*An analysis of the representativeness and ethical distribution of
various museums' art collections will primarily advise museum
acquisition teams of where their collections lack in terms of diversity.
Our team chose to analyze the distributions of artwork and artists
represented in the Tate, MoMA, and Block museum collections through
variables such as artwork medium, artwork size, artwork age, artist
nationality, and artist distribution. Additionally, we provide intervals
of creation dates corresponding to different artwork variables, such as
medium, in order to provide acquisition teams at museums with a medium
to look into acquiring if they are looking for an artwork of a specific
creation date*.
:::

</div>
:::

::: {#background-motivation .section .level2 number="1"}
## [1]{.header-section-number} Background / Motivation {#background-motivation .anchored number="1" anchor-id="background-motivation"}

Museums are a primary mode of connecting people with art--they are
integral to our perceptions of art, the people who create it, and our
subconscious conclusions regarding what art is deemed important versus
what art is not. In more recent times, the practice of ethically
cataloging artist and artwork data has become a more prominent topic of
discussion in museums internationally. Museums are growing aware of
"reevaluat\[ing\] their practices in order to foster inclusion" \[1\].
Many museums express their commitment to ethically representing
marginalized groups as the vast majority of the historical art canon has
been largely formed through a westernized lens. Our team was interested
in the demographic of artists and dates of creation for works in major
Euro-centrically focused museums, and the patterns that emerge.
Additionally, because the nature of data analysis is to distill artwork
to its raw descriptive characteristics (artist, materials, date of
creation, etc.), this kind of exploration inspired our team to look at
art in a way that goes beyond the visual norm. We were interested to see
how we can gain a new understanding of art and museums through
data-driven research, while also making interesting discoveries that
could inform recommendations to museum curators and other interested
parties.
:::

::: {#problem-statement .section .level2 number="2"}
## [2]{.header-section-number} Problem statement {#problem-statement .anchored number="2" anchor-id="problem-statement"}

The four analysis questions our group chose to focus on are outlined
below. These questions delve into four different areas that help paint a
comprehensive picture of the demographics and diversity of artwork and
artists characteristics, while also illuminating and potholes in the
data cataloging of certain museums

1.  When are artworks with unknown creation dates most likely created
    based on other artwork characteristics?

2.  What materials and dimensions are most popular in each museum's
    collection? Why might these differ/prove to be similar? Have certain
    materials become more popular as we have progressed into the
    twenty-first century?

3.  How old are the artworks in the collections of each museum? How many
    years after creation are artworks acquired by museums?

4.  What is the demographic of the artists represented through the MoMA
    and Tate Museum's collections? Are there trends nationality or
    gender overall? How does this data compare to the demographic of
    artists at a smaller, university museum like the Block?
:::

::: {#data-sources .section .level2 number="3"}
## [3]{.header-section-number} Data sources {#data-sources .anchored number="3" anchor-id="data-sources"}

To conduct our analysis, we utilized multiple open-access datasets,
released to the public by the MoMA and Tate museums. More specifically,
the MoMA artwork dataset contains 140,848 entries, which represent the
entirety of the art pieces "that have been accessioned into MoMA's
collection and cataloged in \[their\] database" \[2\]. The MoMA data for
artwork includes the date of acquisition. The MoMA artists dataset
specifically contains 15,243 entries, each unique, and represents all
the artists who are featured in MoMA's collection through their artworks
and have been cataloged in the MoMA database. The specific, pertinent
variables present in this dataset for MoMA are, the artists' names,
nationalities, genders, birth years, and death years. The Tate artwork
dataset contains information for the some 70,000 artworks that Tate
owns. This open-access datasource was last updated in 2014. The artists
dataset for Tate has information such as name, gender, yearOfBirth,
yearOfDeath, placeOfBirth, and placeOfDeath for about 3,500 associated
artists. Missing data is present in these four datasets and both museums
deem these entries as "not curatorially" approved. However, we feel as
though the data provided in the open-access files provides enough
information to perform analysis of the demographics of artists and
artworks represented in these collections. Finally, to supplement the
above datasets, our group created datasets for the collection of
artwork/artists at the Block Museum of Art on Northwestern campus. To
create csv files for these two areas of interest, we created a full
DataFrame for all artwork information and a full DataFrame for all
artist information found in the Block's website. This data was held in
multiple pages of data tables, which we imported and concatenated
together to create comprehensive DataFrames that were then translated
into csv files. Unfortunately, the Block data lacked a lot of the
variables present in the MoMA and Tate datasets, so this data could only
be used for comparison in certain analysis topics, such as gender and
nationality distribution of artists represented in the museums.

**The links to our data sources are in references** ,**Tabular data for
artists is in appendix**.
:::

::: {#stakeholders .section .level2 number="4"}
## [4]{.header-section-number} Stakeholders {#stakeholders .anchored number="4" anchor-id="stakeholders"}

The pertinent stakeholders to our analysis of the equal representation
and ethical cataloging of major international art museums are
individually elaborated on below.

Museum acquisition teams, as well as curators and collectors will be
interested in the patterns/trends in our analysis that display
distributions that deviate from their goals and pledges. As those
responsible for representing art on a prestigious platform like that of
MoMA and Tate, understanding where their collection falls short may help
them know where to increase funding or focus their acquisitions.

Museum attendees are concerned with viewing an art museum with a vast
selection of art exhibitions with beautiful artworks of different
cultures and stories. Museums have a responsibility to present artworks
that are representative of different cultures/historical facets. An
artwork collection that is not varied is limiting public perception of
art.

Art history or museum researchers and similar people in academia may be
limited due to the fact that Tate and MoMA do not possess a
representative collection of different historical art canons or art
created by underrepresented groups. They may find our data analysis to
be useful in regards to providing a guide to museums on where to focus
acquisitions in order to be more ethical and representative in their
collections. Museum researchers also might find trends regarding mediums
in relation to time reveal new things about the history of artwork in
museums.
:::

::: {#data-quality-check-cleaning-preparation .section .level2 number="5"}
## [5]{.header-section-number} Data quality check / cleaning / preparation {#data-quality-check-cleaning-preparation .anchored number="5" anchor-id="data-quality-check-cleaning-preparation"}

The first step in using the artwork datasets was to prepare the columns
which signified creation date. We wanted the creation dates to be
numeric objects, rather than strings. These strings were inconsistent in
format (i.e. "Designed 1912, drawn 1914" and "ca. 1946-47"). To extract
the creation date, we first changed all of the NaN values in the column
from floats to strings. Next, we found the year values occurring in the
strings using findall() under the 're' library. We then had a list of
lists containing the years as strings. From here, each list of strings
was passed through a series of if statements. If there was only one,
four digit string in the list, that string would serve as the creation
date. If there were two four digit strings that were less than 10 years
apart, the average of these numbers would serve as the creation date.
The output was a list of lists, most of which contained one, four digit
string. There were still some unique dates that required individual
manipulation, and thus these values were not included in the following
analysis.

``` {.sourceCode .python .code-with-copy}
#BLOCK: year preparation
import re
block_works = pd.read_csv('Desktop/STAT3031/block_works.csv')
list_of_values = block_works['Date'].to_list()

#if the value is nan, change the value to an 'x'
for i in range(6074):
    if type(list_of_values[i])==float:
        list_of_values[i] = 'x'

#now every date is a string.
block_works['Date'] = list_of_values

c = []
for i in range(6074):
    c.append(re.findall('\d+', list_of_values[i] ))

#if there is only one four digit number, we want to use that number. 
for i in range(6074):
    if len(c[i])>0:
        for j in c[i]:
            if len(j)<4:
                c[i].remove(j)

#if there are multiple four digit numbers that are less than 5 years apart, we should take the average of the two.
#if there are more than two numbers detected, we will not be including the artwork in analysis
for i in range(6074):
    if len(c[i])==2:
        if ((len(c[i][0])==4) & (len(c[i][1])==4)& (int(c[i][1]) - int(c[i][0]) <5)):
            c[i] = [(int(c[i][0]) + int(c[i][1]))/2]
    elif len(c[i])>3:
        c[i] = []

good_indexes = []
for i in range(6074):
    if len(c[i])==1:
        good_indexes.append(i)
        c[i]=int(c[i][0])
block_works['Date'] = c
block_list = ["Block" for x in good_indexes]

block_works_cleaned = block_works.iloc[good_indexes,:].reset_index()
block_works_cleaned['Date'] = pd.to_numeric(block_works_cleaned['Date'])
```

For the artist datasets for each museum, the pertinent columns on gender
and nationality needed to be cleaned before using for analysis and
visualizations. The Block museum failed to possess data for artist
gender, so only the Tate and MoMA datasets were analyzed in this
respect. For the Gender column in both artists' datasets, the counts of
each value were visualized in a series to primarily determine if any of
the values in the column needed to be cleaned. The Tate dataset only
included two values for the Gender column, "Male" and "Female".
Therefore, this column was left alone. In the MoMA dataset however, the
values in the gender column took on multiple values that needed to be
combined to create clean data. The values in the MoMA gender column were
"Male", "Female", "male", "Non-Binary", "female", and "Non-binary".
These values were cleaned with an applied lambda function that
consolidated the similar value names together to create three
categories: "Male", "Female", and "Non-Binary".

The missing values in the Tate artist dataset made up less than 4% of
the dataset, so the assumption was made that the overall distributions
would not be affected by ignoring these values. Even though the MoMA
dataset has a significantly larger amount of missing values, we felt as
though the assumption still held in regards to gender distribution.
Additionally, taking into account the ethical cataloging notion held by
many major museums, we assumed that if a gender was missing, then an
artist either did not want their gender specified, or the museum did not
want to assume a gender of the artist based off of, say, the artist's
name.

For the nationalities of the artists, major cleaning was required for
the Block and Tate museum datasets as they did not have a singular
nationality column. MoMA did not need to be majorly cleaned as it
already possessed a specific nationality column. For the Block Museum
artist dataset, the nationality could be observed as a part of the
string in the date column. If the date column was completely empty for
an entry, we dropped the row. For the remaining entries, the Date column
had to be split where commas were present into multiple columns that we
extracted in a new dataframe. We assumed that the nationality would be
in its own section based on comma splicing, most likely in the first
spliced column judging based on the general format of the Date column in
this Block artists dataset. If there was no value in the second column
of the separate columns representing the split Date column, the
nationality was the value assumed to be in the first column. Then, if
the string "founded", or "-" (representing the dash between dates, which
was also present in the date column) was found in the first column being
cleaned to ideally only contain the artist nationalities, these values
were dropped. Finally, a couple similar values for nationality were
combined into the same value for ease in distribution. For example,
'American installation artist' was cleaned to be included in the
'American' nationality group.

For the Tate artists, there was also no nationality column explicitly
present. To display this distribution, the birthplace of the artist was
assumed to be analogous with their nationality, as the country in which
one is born is a country the person has citizenship in. Thus, the
'placeOfBirth' column in the Tate dataset was cleaned to adequately
display the distribution of the main nationalities represented by the
artists present in this museum's collection. For example, artists with
'Deuschland' or 'Germany' mentioned in the string under the
'placeOfBirth' column were cleaned to be grouped in the 'German'
nationality. This process was applied using an applied lambda function
which completed analogous processes the German example but for many
countries. Entries that had no value in the variable 'placeOfBirth' were
dropped, which was less than 15% of the data. We assumed that this would
not drastically skew the distribution of nationality greatly. While we
could have imputed nationality for these missing values based on the
'placeOfDeath' variable, we were wary to do so based on the fact that
artists could have moved countries, and their location/country of death
would not necessarily reflect accurately on nationality. Thus, the
distribution is based primarily off of artists whose places of Birth
were present in the dataset.

::: {#exploratory-data-analysis .section .level2 number="6"}
## [6]{.header-section-number} Exploratory Data Analysis {#exploratory-data-analysis .anchored number="6" anchor-id="exploratory-data-analysis"}

::: {#analysis-1 .section .level3 number="6.1"}
### [6.1]{.header-section-number} Analysis 1 {#analysis-1 .anchored number="6.1" anchor-id="analysis-1"}

*By Kenneth Yeon*

Determining an estimation of when an artwork with an unknown date was
created requires us to explore trends of pieces that have known dates.
After reading the cleaned csv files, we created separate data
frames--one containing artworks with known dates, and another containing
artworks without dates. This allows us to exclusively work with the art
pieces with known dates, and apply those trends to the artworks with
unknown dates. A great way to approximate the dates of the mysterious
artworks would be to examine the trends for artworks of similar mediums.
Throughout time, there have been trends for different mediums of art.
For instance, painting was an extremely popular medium during the
renaissance, and digital art is a growing trend in the modern age.
Analyzing these trends would provide us with a span of time where we
could assume an artwork with a missing date should have been created.

::: {.cell execution_count="128"}
Code

After clearing the outliers from the data, we created graphs that
depicted the distribution of mediums throughout time. These
distributions confirm that mediums grew and declined in popularity
throughout time. Each medium had a range of years where it faced its
peak in popularity. Finally, to answer our question, we calculated a
confidence interval that allows us to be 95% confident that an artwork
of a given medium was created between the ranges of the resulting
interval. For instance, at MoMA, we are 95% confident that a letterpress
artwork was created between 1934 and 1935.

::: {.cell execution_count="76"}
Code

::: {#cb12 .sourceCode .cell-code}
``` {.sourceCode .python .code-with-copy}
#finding outliers for moma
moma_no_outliers = moma_med[0:0]
for i in moma_unknown_med:
    temp = moma_med.loc[moma_med['Medium'] == i]
    q1, q3= np.percentile(temp.Date,[25,75])
    iqr = q3 - q1
    lower_bound = q1 - 1.5*iqr
    upper_bound = q3 + 1.5*iqr

    no_outliers = temp[((temp.Date>=lower_bound) & (temp.Date<=upper_bound))]
    moma_no_outliers = pd.concat([moma_no_outliers, no_outliers])
    
#finding outliers for tate
tate_no_outliers = tate_med[0:0]
for i in tate_unknown_med:
    temp = tate_med.loc[tate_med['medium'] == i]
    q1, q3= np.percentile(temp.year,[25,75])
    iqr = q3 - q1
    lower_bound = q1 - 1.5*iqr
    upper_bound = q3 + 1.5*iqr

    no_outliers = temp[((temp.year>=lower_bound) & (temp.year<=upper_bound))]
    tate_no_outliers = pd.concat([tate_no_outliers, no_outliers])

#function for calculating confidence interval
def standard_dev(df, medium, date):
    mean = df[date].mean()
    sd = df[date].std()
    n = len(df)
    Zstar = 1.96
    se = sd/np.sqrt(n)
    lower = round(mean - Zstar * se)
    upper = round(mean + Zstar * se)
    print(f'{medium}: ({lower}, {upper})')
```

### [6.2]{.header-section-number} Analysis 2 {#analysis-2 .anchored number="6.2" anchor-id="analysis-2"}

*By Riley Otsuki*

### [6.3]{.header-section-number} Analysis 3 {#analysis-3 .anchored number="6.3" anchor-id="analysis-3"}

*By Lila Weiner*

As previously mentioned, the first step in exploring artwork age was to
prepare the columns which signified creation date. To account for common
cases of creation dates, we subsetted these inputs using a series of
filtering processes. After addressing these cases, we converted the year
column to numeric in order to analyze the variable. To create a new
"artwork age" column, we subtracted the creation date from 2022. We also
added a column to each dataset, which specified the museum. This column
proved to be useful after we concatenated the artwork ages of all of the
museums.

::: {.cell execution_count="241"}
Code

::: {#cb36 .sourceCode .cell-code}
``` {.sourceCode .python .code-with-copy}
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import sklearn as sk
import seaborn as sb

#Creating the artwork age variable. 
block_list = ["Block" for x in range(block_works_cleaned.shape[0])]

moma_works_cleaned['Museum'] = moma_list

tate_works_cleaned['Museum'] = tate_list
```

:::

Once we added the new columns, we computed the summary statistics of
artwork age. Initially, we subsetted the three datasets for the new
"museum name" and "artwork age" columns, and then vertically
concatenated these subsetted datasets. From here, we grouped the
concatenated dataset by "museum name", and computed the mean, median,
and standard deviation of artwork age using .agg(). The standard
deviation of the Block museum is higher than the other two museums,
which indicates the larger variation of the museum's collection. The
Block museum's variation is notable, as it proves that a small scale
museum has a relative ability to collect old and new artworks alike.

The artwork age distribution of Tate's collection is significantly older
than the Moma and Block museums. While the Tate distribution is centered
around 150 years, most of the Moma and Block artworks are under 100
years old. Generally, the distribution trends align with the mean age of
the three museums, as the mean age for Tate is approximately 72 years
older than the Block, and 90 years older than the Moma. Tate's older
artwork collection could be attributed to the museum age. The Tate
Museum was founded in 1897, and is the oldest of the three museums. Tate
museum is also located in England, and is in closer geographic proximity
to artworks that were produced in Eastern centered art movements. Also,
the continued act of preserving older artworks is costly: the physical
elements of an aged artwork require meticulous upkeep, temperature
regulation and protection. Hence, the Tate museum is opportunely
situated in regard to location and time, and might also have more
resources to collect older artworks. Following the stacked histogram of
artwork age, we decided to compare artwork age and acquisition year. The
acquisition date column is only present in the Moma and Tate datasets,
so the Block data was not used in this regard. For the two datasets, we
made a new column "acquisition age" that is the acquisition year
subtracted by the creation year. Acquisition date was initially
represented by a year-month-day string in both dataframes, so we
subsetted for the four digit year in order to complete the subtraction.
Finally, we plotted the "acquisition age" using displot() to visualize
the distribution.

``` {.sourceCode .python .code-with-copy}
for i in range(128624):

moma_works_cleaned['DateAcquired'] = pd.to_numeric(moma_works_cleaned['DateAcquired'])
moma_works_cleaned['Age_at_acquisition'] = moma_works_cleaned['DateAcquired']-moma_works_cleaned['Date']

sb.set(font_scale = 1)
```

::: {#analysis-4 .section .level3 number="6.4"}
### [6.4]{.header-section-number} Analysis 4 {#analysis-4 .anchored number="6.4" anchor-id="analysis-4"}

*By Gabrielle Bliss*

The demographic analysis of artists represented in the MoMA, Tate, and
Block museums utilized the museum artist databases the most, and aims to
depict the representation of artists by nationality and gender in order
to inform future acquisitions. As aforementioned in the background of
our project, a general consensus among museums today is that their
collections should avoid overlooking historically marginalized groups,
and by performing an analysis of nationality and gender of represented
artists in these three museums, acquisitionists and other stakeholders
will be informed on how to better make ethical acquisitions.

Using the clean data in the gender columns of the Tate and MoMA
datasets, I was able to create a visualization of gender distribution
for both of these museums using a stacked barplot. This stacked barplot
visualized the distribution between "Male" and "Female" genders for both
museums, while also displaying the proportion of artists that identify
as "Non-Binary" in the MoMA's collection. In order to achieve this
particular visualization, the crosstab() function had to be used on both
of the gender columns for both museums, with a normalizing argument in
order to visualize proportions. A distribution visualization with
regards to proportion of genders in represented artists was ideal since
the sample size of genders for artists in both museums differed.

::: {.cell execution_count="169"}
Code

::: {#cb44 .sourceCode .cell-code}
``` {.sourceCode .python .code-with-copy}
gender_proportion_tatemuseum = pd.crosstab(index='Tate', columns=tate_artists['gender'], normalize='index')
gender_proportion_moma = pd.crosstab(index='MoMA', columns=moma_artists['Gender0'], normalize='index')
gender_proportion = pd.concat([gender_proportion_moma, gender_proportion_tatemuseum], axis = 0)
gender_proportion.loc['Tate', 'Non-Binary'] = 0

ax = gender_proportion.plot.bar(stacked=True,ylabel = 'Gender Distribution',figsize=(15, 10), xlabel = '')
ax.tick_params(axis = 'both',labelsize=10)
ax.figure.set_figwidth(7)
ax.figure.set_figheight(5)
```

![](data:image/png;base64,){.img-fluid}
:::

Once the stacked barplot was visualized, one can observe that the
artists represented in the Tate museum's artwork collection are highly
dominated by male-identifying artists; specifically, the visualization
suggests that greater than 80% of Tate artists with gender specified in
the dataset are male-identifying. Less than 20% are female-identifying.
The represented artists in MoMA's collection has a higher proportion of
female-identifying artists, though not by much. This distribution is
about 80:20 male to female-identifying artists, with a sliver of the
gender proportions representing the non-binary artists. The small
proportion of non-binary artists represented in the MoMA data might be
reflective of the smaller proportion of this gender identity in the
overall population of artists internationally, but analyzing this data
through the lens of ethical representation and acquisition suggests that
this should be an area of focus for museums to improve representation of
artists in their collections.

It is important to note that the visualization calculates proportion
without taking missing values into account. When calculating
percentages/proportions of gender represented in the entire dataset
(including missing values), the proportions are slightly different, as
they are being divided by all entries, including the missing values. In
the Tate dataset, very specifically 3.3% of the represented artists have
a missing gender when cataloged, 14.8% of the represented artists are
female-identifying, and 82.0% are male-identifying. There are 2895
male-identifying artists listed, and 521 female-identifying.

::: {#cb49 .sourceCode .cell-code}
``` {.sourceCode .python .code-with-copy}
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

def pct_remove(limit):
    """Remove percent on small slices."""
    def inner_pct(pct):
        return ('%.0f%%' % pct) if pct > limit else ''
    return inner_pct

#defining Seaborn color palette to use
colors = sns.color_palette('pastel')[0:len(moma_artists.Nationality.value_counts())]

data = moma_artists.Nationality.value_counts(normalize=True)

#create pie chart
momapie = plt.pie(x=data, labels = data.index, colors = colors, autopct=pct_remove(1), radius=3)
```

::: {#conclusions .section .level2 number="7"}
## [7]{.header-section-number} Conclusions {#conclusions .anchored number="7" anchor-id="conclusions"}

1.  After analyzing the trends for dated artworks, we were able to
    conclude on a confidence interval that allows museums to be 95%
    confident about the date an undated artwork was created. Based on
    these confidence intervals, we can conclude on the historical
    context behind the artwork, which ultimately provides deeper insight
    into the artwork's meaning and significance.

2.  In terms of mediums, both museums heavily featured mediums related
    to photography which can be justified by the fact that both Museums
    have an emphasis on modern works, especially MoMA. When looking at
    mediums in relation to time however, we saw that all of the top 5
    mediums had a "peak" in terms of artworks done with that medium,
    suggesting that mediums are only popular for a short period of time.
    Lastly, when looking at dimensions both museums seemed to suggest
    that artworks have been growing in size since the 1800s, with the
    Tate museum having older works that vary a lot in size.

3.  Generally, the Tate museum has an older collection of artworks than
    the Moma and Block museums. This may be due to the geographic
    location, size, and status of the Tate museum. Additionally, the
    Tate and Moma typically acquire artworks a few years after the
    artwork was created, according to the two histograms.

4.  Distribution of gender in both major museums analyzed (Tate and
    MoMA) is heavily dominated by male-identifying artists; around 80%
    of artists represented in artwork collections are male. The MoMA had
    slightly better diversity in terms of representing a slightly higher
    proportion of female artists and including non-binary artists in
    their collection. The distributions of nationality highlight the
    dominance of European and American artists represented in these
    museums. We can possibly attribute this to the fact that the museum
    collections also consist of artwork "gifts" from locals and alumni
    rather than specific acquisitions by the museum. In future analyses,
    data regarding these artists and demographics could be weighted by
    the amount of art pieces they have provided to the museums'
    collections.
:::

::: {#recommendations-to-stakeholders .section .level2 number="8"}
## [8]{.header-section-number} Recommendations to stakeholders {#recommendations-to-stakeholders .anchored number="8" anchor-id="recommendations-to-stakeholders"}

In our first analysis, our stakeholders are presented with a 95%
confidence interval that estimates when an artwork was created. The
confidence intervals present art curators the chance to realize further
trends of artworks throughout time. With this information, curators can
better understand the artwork and its role in the historical context of
when it was created, and refer to these estimated intervals when looking
for an artwork from a specific time period to acquire. Also, art
curators can present visitors with more accurate information about the
artwork dates through our confidence intervals, which presents a deeper
comprehension of trends of acquired artworks.

The second analysis depicts the most pervasive mediums featured in the
museums which to stakeholders, specifically museum curators, signals
that there needs to be more diversity in terms of the mediums of the
work. A potential solution to this would be to introduce artworks with
mediums that originated from underrepresented countries as opposed to
popular mediums that feature mainly European artists. Further, looking
at the dimensions, there seems to be an upward trend in the size of
artworks since the 1800s. For art researchers there is an interesting
trend in terms of art dimensions in relation to time.

While all three museums contain both old and new artworks, there are
measures that can be taken in order to ensure that smaller scale museums
can present historical works of art to their audiences. We suggest that
larger museums, such as the Tate museum, loan older artworks to small
scale museums for temporary exhibitions. Temporary exhibitions succeed
in spreading artwork of differing ages to new audiences, and promoting
the museum that is lending the art. There are financial costs of
temporary exhibitions, since they require considerable effort to
transport artworks carefully. However, two museums in close proximity
could organize a temporary exhibition without shipping artworks across
states/countries. For instance, the Art Institute of Chicago and the
Block Museum might consider collaborating in order to bring works from
the Art Institute to Northwestern's campus. There are also organizations
in place to guide the creation of temporary exhibitions, such as the
Touring Exhibitions Group, based in the United Kingdom.

The analysis of artist demographics primarily provides the most
pertinent, specific recommendations to museum acquisition teams and
collectors, as opposed to the other stakeholders that our project could
be applicable to. When making acquisitions, in order to further
diversify the artists represented in the various museums' collections,
acquisition teams can look to these distributions to inform where they
are lacking in terms of representation. For example, all analyzed
museums could increase their representation of artists with Asian
nationalities. The Tate and MoMA should focus acquisitions on works done
by artists that are female-identifying or of another gender than male
when looking to diversify their collections in terms of these variables.
:::
